All files can be found under the "Thing Files'' tab right below the photos of our hands. Please click download all file to get all components of the hands.
For More information on assembly or the research, please go to http://www.cyborgbeast.org To make the Normal Hand Version, print and scale the following:
1x Right OR Left Palm
1x Normal Gauntlet or Normal Gauntlet w Tensioner
4x Finger Phal
4x Finger w Bumps OR Finger wo Bumps
1x Thumb Phalange
1x Thumb Finger w Bumps OR Thumb Finger wo Bumps
To make the No Thumb Hand Version, print and scale the following:
1x R No Thumb Palm OR L No Thumb Palm
1x R One Hinge Gauntlet OR L One Hinge Gauntlet
4x Finger Phal
4x Finger w Bumps OR Finger wo Bumps Ulnar/Radial Deviation Hand, Movable Thumb Hand, and Cyborg Arm --> Soon to be released. Most voluntary closing devices including this design need sufficient wrist movement and strength for proper function. This design doesn't require Orthoplastic. The fingers are designed for better gripping and to avoid over extension of the proximal phalange and distal finger segment. It fits a 1 to 2 mm cabling and elastic bands.
Acknowledgements: The Cyborg Beast is a remix of the snap together Robohand (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:92937) and the original Robohand (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:44150).

Infill: Depends on age. We usually do 30% infill.
Number of Shells? 2
Temp? Depends on Plastic recommendations. But 230 c is safe estimate for all types.
Speed? For better quality, lower your speed to 60mm/sec extrusion and 90mm/sec for traveling
Orientation: The same as the objects load onto the build plate. We designed the STL files for ease of use so you do not need to change much. See Manual as a PDF files.

comments.author: Kolia

comments.text:
That's how I print the palm as well. One thing that helped is using Simplify3D as a slicer, as it generates support that's easy to remove. In particular, it can leave a one layer gap between the support and the supported material, so the palm ends up resting on top of the support, not bonded with it, so the support is quite easy to remove. The other fantastic thing about Simplify3D is that you can manually control where it generates support, so you can (for example) generate support for the arch of the palm, but not in the screw holes and bridges over the knuckles. The result is that the print is very clean, and the support is easy to remove.
The newer versions of MakerWare also do a pretty good job with support, but IMO Simplify3D, with its manual controls, gives the best results.

title: Dyson cyclone based dust extractor - simple build

description.text:
Recently I've found a need for a dust extractor to deal with woodworking dust. I didn't want to spend much, and I wanted one that didn't take up much space.

You can't use a vacuum cleaner alone for dust extraction, as the dust very rapidly clogs up the vacuum canister (followed shortly by clogging the vacuum filters). By using an additional cyclone system above a bucket, you can extract dust for ages as the bucket and secondary cyclone prevent anything getting through to the vacuum.

This is a very easy build. Just print out the pieces, cut a few holes in a bit of plywood and if you're feeling keen, route a groove in the plywood to match the bucket.

What you need:
A Dyson DC14 canister. I got mine for $30 from a parts sale.
A vacuum hose,
A vacuum cleaner,
Some adhesive backed foam,
Some screws,
Some 12mm plywood or other decent wood,
A reasonably robust bucket. Keep in mind it will be under vacuum pressure, and needs to have decent strength walls.

1) Print all the goodies.
2) Cut your wood slightly larger than the top of the bucket, and cut a hole around 160mm across in the centre of the wood for the Dyson canister
3) Route a groove (optional) and place the foam on the plywood to seal the bucket. If you have a router, you could use my router circle jig to make perfect circles. https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2611305
4) Place the 'Extractor lid guides.stl' under the wood so that they align the foam and wood with the bucket lip.
5) Screw the 'Extractor cyclone mount.stl' to the plywood on the opposite side to the foam.
6) Pry the lower door of the Dyson DC14 canister (Carefully. Don't break the plastic. I used a small screwdriver to help).
7) Stick the Dyson canister into the attachment. Place the 'Extractor vent cover.stl' over the central hole of the canister. (You need it to seal the bottom of the Dyson canister. This is usually sealed by the lower door.
8) Put all the adapters in place, attach a vacuum cleaner and suck.

Diameters for these components are based on:
Vacuum cleaner hose - 41.7 mm external Ø.
Dust extractor hose at canister - 53.5 mm internal Ø
Dust extractor hose for tool - 34.75 mm external Ø
Tool dust extraction port - 37mm external Ø

If you have different diameters you'll need to modify or design a different adaptor.

title: Ryobi Li-Ion Battery Pack
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
While working on my Lack project my 10 year old Ryobi batteries which had been rebuilt a couple times just weren't cutting it anymore... So I went looking for a better option...

3D printer - Check...
ton of 18650 cells - Check...

I found a couple reference models on thingyverse that I've used before (like enif's battery case design ideas, and leaning on Simhopp's modeling work on the case I redrew it, modified it and built a couple extra parts to suit my needs...

In the end, this pack is ~50% the weight of a Ryobi NiCad case (600g vs 1kg) and has almost 4x the capacity (~1200mah NiCad vs ~5000mah (2x2500mah) LiIon). Images of the scale included, I didn't know it was going to be this light... (on the downside, my large drill now can tip it over lol, might have to add weight.

Let me state this here first:

  1. LITHIUM ION BATTERIES CAN BE VERY DANGEROUS! Improper charging, accidental shorting of cables, etc... can cause them to catch fire and/or explode
  2. If your not confident you know what you're doing, I'd go but another battery pack, its much safer. I'm not going to go into too much detail on the wiring for that reason, if you understand it, it'll be straight forward.
  3. DO NOT charge ths pack on the factory charger. Why not? its designed for NiCad or NiMH packs, this pack also has no temperature sensing. Remove the cells and charge seperately in a proper charger OR, like I did, add balance leads and build a adapter to connect it to a proper LiIon charger. What happens if you do? See #1...

Comments greatly appreciated, let me know what you think!

Build & Assembly Notes:

This could be fun...
I tried to document the process in pictures, they should be in order and I hope its fairly straight forward.
let me know if you need much more information on a particular step.

General:

  • Print the parts
  • wire the battery box
  • build & wire the contacts ( I used brass sheet cut 12.5mm wide (~1/2") and ~50mm long, stick it in the top and roll it over, bend it around the keeper posts, solder on the wires)
  • put battery box in the case bottom
  • put contacts in the top and secure with a screw (pulled from a bag of screws from toys that have died)
  • fit release clips in with springs (salvaged mine from 2 ball point pens)
  • screw top on bottom (I used 4 3/4" #6 screws, was all out of plastic taping screws)
  • insert batteries... (BIG WARNING! MAKE SURE THEY GO IN THE RIGHT WAY!!! Each stack of two go the same direction, orientation is on the bottom of the battery box)
  • slide door into place
  • Profit!

The parts below are required to finish the pack:

1x ryobi battery box
1x ryobi battery door
1x ryobi case bottom
1x ryobi case top
1x ryobi contact holder
2x ryobi release clip

Also:
4x #6x3/4" screws (or M3 which is what I built it around)
1x "small" screw (I don't have a size, I printed a small hole and found a screw to fit)
2x springs - I stole these out of 2 Pentel ball point pens I had lying around.

description.text: A key design goal in my LACK enclosure (see: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2613678) was quick and easy removal of the top. Most other designs set the spool on top of the cabinet, meaning you need to unload the filament to get the top off completely. I’ve rigged it to mount below the printer and feed up via a pulley of sorts.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Infill:

20%

I reckon you could build a carousel of spools (radiating out from the centre, Rockettes 42nd Street-style) under there actually, which would make for easy filament changes. For now I’m just:

  • reusing the one metal spool bracket that came with my Wanhao i3 Plus
  • one M8 x 90mm bolt through two M8 x 50mm o/d washers sandwiching an M8 x 30mm o/d washer between them
  • two ‘Parametric Filament Spool Hub with 608ZZ bearing’ from https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:605360

The filament comes up through the tabletop via what is basically a funnel, to guide it from various positions on the spool towards the hole at the top. My inspiration came from a kitchen funnel, but I see others came to the same conclusion in https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2361640 and https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2098879. The ‘Self adjusting filament guide for Ikea Lack table enclosure’ at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2427961 is an interesting idea that would work as well. You could also fit some sort of ‘filament cleaner’ sponge thingy in here if you wanted.

I really wanted to make the filament’s journey ‘up and over’ as effortless as possible for the printer. Hence the 608ZZ bearings on the spool hub underneath, and two in my Wanhao top-mount for the ‘Customizable Filament Spool’ at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2158282. The top spool is that large in diameter because (a) “The larger the wheel, the greater the mechanical advantage in overcoming friction”, (b) the filament can come up in a straight line from the bottom, and down in the centre of the X-axis gantry (see photos).

The bolt holes in my spool top-mount are spaced for a Wanhao i3, reusing the two holes for the spool bracket they supply (but using longer bolts). You may need to adjust spacing for your printer.

One thing when you’re drilling that hole in your LACK tabletop for this… I placed it with a plumb line directly down from the spindle hub’s edge. After threading some filament through I realised that duh, plastic filament is not string, and it retains some of the curve set into it after sitting wound on a spool its whole life. So the hole – and the spool mounting directly below the hole – should be closer to the tabletop edge (i.e. further to the side of the printer) than you might first think. It’s not a big deal, but if you’re a perfectionist it’s annoying to see it slightly out of line.

I have a couple V623ZZ 12x3x4 mm V-groove pulleys (http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/V623ZZ-12x3x4-mm-V-Groove-Sealed-Guide-Pulley-Rail-Ball-Bearing/151937961360) attached at the base of the printer to help guide the filament. I replaced the Wanhao socket cap machine bolts down there with slightly longer ones to mount these on. To be honest they don’t really do much, but they were so tiny and cute I just had to buy them :)

Hole in tabletop should have been a little further to the right, grrrr....

Top Spool

I printed my top spool (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2158282) with the following settings (Thingiverse Customizer is super-cool, btw)

Size

  • Spindle Diameter of the center spindle hole in mm = 11
  • Spindle Od Diam of spindle that filament wraps around in mm = 90
  • Spool Od Overall outside diameter of spool in mm = 120
  • Spool Width Overall width of spool in mm = 20 (the smallest width currently available in Customizer for this, which really is too wide for one strand of filament (leaves like 14mm between the spool walls!) as the X-axis gantry doesn’t move on the Y-axis anyway)

Spokes

  • Wall Style Style of spool walls = spoked
  • Spoke Count Number of spokes = 6
  • Spoke Width Spoke width, in mm = 12

Misc

  • Spool Wall Thickness of spool walls in mm = 3 (they probably didn’t need to be this thick, it’s not like you’re wrapping a ton of filament around it)

Notes:
  • You might be able to get away without supports. I used them in the larger screw holes and the 'notch' at the base of the female plug shell.
  • The shell design is (intentionally) a very tight fit for a male-female pair of 12V CCTV power plugs (2.1mm x 5.5mm). You may need to play with scaling/etc. to fit the plugs you use.
  • I slice using Simplify3D set to a ‘horizontal size compensation’ of -0.20mm… which conveniently means I can design in AutoCAD with no gaps between parts, and that -0.20mm creates the nice gap for me. Perhaps naughty :)

My mains power bar and a 12V transformer are all mounted under the base that the printer sits on, nicely out of sight. But the lights (and whatever else like fans, a Pi, webcam, etc.) in the top enclosure need DC power too. Sure it’s easy to just disconnect a connector or two before lifting off the enclosure, but I wanted something more elegant – which wouldn’t need me to remember to disconnect/connect cables!

I considered running the cable up through one of the LACK legs (they are mostly hollow) and integrating a connector right into the base mount of the leg (see my https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2613678). But that felt a little over-complicated, and I was leery about having 1/4 of the top enclosure’s weight resting on top of the power connection. So I built something attached to the side of a back leg, and tidied it up with some cable channel covers in the same PLA material.

The shell design is (intentionally) a very tight fit for a male-female pair of 12V CCTV power plugs (2.1mm x 5.5mm, I used these: https://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/5-Pair-DC-Power-Socket-Plug-Screw-Terminal-12V-Volt-CCTV-Adaptor-2-1mm-x-5-5mm/122240856534). You may need to play with scaling/etc. to fit the plugs you use.

Female plug shell with cap removed

The height for the (male) base is the thickness of a LACK tabletop (50mm) minus the underside exterior shell thickness (2.7mm-ish). You only need to cut a square hole in the table’s top for the base (I used a Dremel), and then a drill hole directly below the square, just big enough to run your cable down through the table’s underside. The rest of the underside supports the shell+plug, particularly when you’re placing the top on its base (i.e. when force is pushing down on the male plug).

Male plug in tabletop, with cap removed

Also as I’m tuning my new Wanhao i3 Plus printer, its dimensional accuracy is still a bit off (maybe I need a finer nozzle than 0.4mm?). So I slice using Simplify3D set to a ‘horizontal size compensation’ of -0.20mm… which conveniently means I can design in AutoCAD with no gaps between parts, and that -0.20mm creates the nice gap for me. This is probably terrible design practice, but for now in my early 3D career it’s working quite well for me. Apologies if it doesn’t for you – polite suggestions welcome.

My first design had a ‘tab’ to screw the top plug shell and cap to the leg (see extra photos). But as I was about to mount those I realised I could do this more elegantly with some ‘blind’ screw holes for the plug shell, and four M3x6mm set screws (a.k.a. ‘grub screws’) for the cap (you do not need a tap and die set for these tiny holes btw, the set screws will basically make their own threads in the plastic). Note the bottom cable channel cover also helps to hold the cap+shell+plug down when you’re placing the top on its base (i.e. when force is pushing up on the female plug).

The cable channel cover is 150mm long, so you’ll need to print a few/adjust to make up the height of your enclosure legs (minus the female cap+shell at the bottom of the leg). Someday I need to learn how to have the Thingiverse Customizer make this an easy parametric setting. I considered making some sort of snap-on cap to hide the cover screws (two per segment in my design), but decided that was a tad overboard.

I don’t know how many connect-disconnect cycles the plugs will handle before they start to fail. Guess I will find out, and they’re not hard to replace (I bought five pairs just in case). The leg mounts from my enclosure design (see: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2613678) do help to ensure they are aligned when coupling, making for a smooth fit and hopefully less wear.

PS. The yellow 'Junction Box Cover for Wago 222/221 Terminal Connectors' is here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2625724

PPS. The lighting is just regular 3528 flexible LED strip/rope lights (cool white / 6000K) cut into four segments, and mounted in slim aluminum (North American spelling) strip light channel with a clear PVC cover. Since there was 16 feet of these lights, I also ran some inside the Wanhao’s top frame. The latter really helps to reduce shadows and illuminate the print bed evenly. The LED set also came with an RF wireless remote dimmer, which is handy. I bought this kit (https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B01IN5BLUG) but there are hundreds of these sets out there.

description.text: There’s nothing 3D print-related about this, other than it fits under my (see: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2613678) and others’ LACK enclosures for 3D printers.

The MDF base is cut from some other IKEA furniture that my neighbour was throwing out (a bit of ‘IKEA reincarnation’). I mounted 35mm x 35mm ‘L-angle’ extruded aluminum (North American spelling) around three sides to keep the LACK from sliding off when rolling it. Main reason I didn’t do the fourth side was because I didn’t want to cut into a fresh new 2 metre length of aluminum for it… but so far having the fourth side open means I don’t have to be so precise about placing the LACK on/in this dolly.

Casters are locking, dual-wheel 50mm ones (https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B071KY2FSQ) but most any will probably do. Obviously you don’t want to go too cheap and risk your precious printer toppling over because of a junk caster. I wanted as much contact with the floor as possible, hence dual wheels to reduce shake in the tower looming over these four little casters.

While writing up my design, I noticed https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2219004 has a somewhat similar idea, but fixed to a plywood base instead of another LACK tabletop like I used. For me, using a third tabletop as a base left me with four extra legs to easily raise the enclosure (see: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2613678).

Blinking lights

  • 5x Yellow LEDs
  • 5x 220 Ohm resistors
  • 1x 9v Battery
  • 1x 9v Battery adapter
  • Wires

Schematics

Assembly

Step 1:
Solder the LEDs with the resistors

Step 2:
Solder the cables following the schema.

Step 3:
Glue the LEDs in the correct position with hot glue. Two LEDs in the eyes and three in the mouth.

Step 4:
Connect the LED cables to an Arduino nano on pins 5 and 6.

Step 5:
Connect the battery and insert the circuit into the pumpkin.

Step 6:
Place the bucket inside the pumpkin.

description.text:
BRIDGE is a ≈8 minute object for tweaking your bridging settings. I think that the most important layer of a bridge is the first layer because it's what everything else builds onto, so we can save a lot of time by printing the first layer only. BRIDGE tests a range of unsupported bridging lengths from 5 mm to 50 mm, in 5 mm increments.

Here's a slow-motion video just because! https://youtu.be/mf-m8x8O7No

Do you just want to know what settings I use in Simplify3D?
  • 75 % bridging extrusion multiplier so that the drooping plastic takes up less space in the Z axis (100 % takes up around 0.15 mm of space).
  • 20 % bridging speed multiplier, which is 15 mm/s from a base speed of 75 mm/s.
  • 100 % fan speed (every layer after my first layer runs at 100 % because I am using my GUST fan duct).
  • Bridging angle is not normally defined, but does have to be defined at 90° for this test object.
  • Apply bridging settings to perimeters set to true.

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.20 mm

Notes:

Important!

Bridging infill angle must be set to 90° so that the infill is oriented lengthwise with the print, otherwise the slicer will try to bridge diagonally along the print and the longest distance you'll get is only 37 mm. This is a setting in Simplify3D (see the photos above), but I am unsure if it exists in Cura or other slicers.

Ich habe eine Halterung für das Windrad https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1659269 von astfaellergerald erstellt, und lasse das Windrad frei ohne Generator in meinem Garten drehen. Siehe Videos und Bilder.

Zur befestigung der Rotorblätter nutze ich M4er Schrauben. Die Halterung an dem Stab wird ebenfalls mit M4er Schrauben fest geklemmt. Der rest der Schrauben sind M3.

Bei fragen gerne in die Kommentare.

Gedruckt wurde das ganze mit 0.35mm layer, 2 perimeter und 40% infill. Bis auf das File windrad_basis_halterung.stl wurde alles ohne Support gedruckt.

Zur befestigung des Rotos an windrad_halter_v2.stl wurde eine M3x35mm Schraube mit 4 10mm Kugellagern verwendet und eingepresst.

windrad_basis_halterung.stl und wird mit dem Oberteil ebenfalls mit einer M3x35mm Schraube und 2 10mm Kugellagern verbunden.

Man kann durch die Basishalterung eine Gewindestande mit Kugellagern stecken und am ende einen Generator anschließen. Allerdings muss man dann die doppelte Schelle nutzen und das Leitwerk nach oben oder unten versetzen damit der Generator platz hat.

Als geeigneten Generator sehe ich dort einen 3 Phasen Brushless Generator wie z.b. diesen hier:
https://www.amazon.de/gp/product/B019K6LN5U/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o08_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Den gibts auch auf aliexpress günstiger.

Für diesen Generator hab ich allerdings keinen Halter entworfen, vielleicht kommt das im laufe der Zeit.

Man sollte auch eine Übersetzung zwischen Windradwelle und Generator vorsehen, da das Windrad, zumindest hier in Mitteldeutschland, nicht genügend Drehzahl erreichen wird, um effektiv Leistung abzugeben.

Natürlich ist das ganze auf nur zur Versorgung kleinerer Bastelprojekte (LEDs, Arduino, laden vom Handy oder sowas) vorgesehen.

Stromerzeugung für den Hausverbrauch ist damit nicht zu bewerkstelligen.

Am besten schaltet man hinter den Generator einen B6 Brückengleichrichter und nutzt dann einen DCDC Wandler der mit den schnell schwankenden Eingangsspannungen klar kommt und diese kompensieren kann.

Ich übernehme keinerlei Haftung für entstandene Schäden durch unsachgemäße benutzung falls damit Strom erzeugt wird um die o.g. Dinge zu laden oder betreiben, ebenso nicht für wegfliegende drehende Teile die Personen oder Sachschaden verursachen.

UPDATE:

Ich habe den Halter der Flügel auf ein 8er Loch umdesigned, die Maße weichen minimal vom Eigentlichen Design ab. Außerdem hab ich das Loch im Halter des Rotos auf 22mm ausgedehnt, damit man auf beiden seiten ein 608zz Kugellager eindrücken/einkleben kann.

Da kann man dann eine M8er Gewindestange vom Rotor durch den Rotorhalter führen und auf der anderen Seite den Generator betreiben, sofern man die Doppelschelle nutzt.

Außerdem verleiht die ganze Konstruktion dem Windrad mehr stabilität. Ich habe manchmal das Gefühl, dass sich bei den hohen Umdrehungsfrequenzen vom Rotor die Kugellager lösen könnten.

Auf Bild IMG_20171102_163812 kann man die neue Halterung für das Windrad sehen. Auf Bild IMG_20171102_171611 sieht man den Aufbau.

UPDATE:

In Verbindung mit der großen Schelle für die Halterung für 608 M8 habe ich die neue Basishalterung (auf den Bildern in Gelb) auf eine M8er Gewindestange gesetzt, und diese in den oberen Teil der Halterung (am Windrad) eingeschraubt, und unten (an dem Teil was mit Kabelbindern befestigt ist) habe ich die Gewindestange durch 2 608er Kugellager laufen lassen. Das verleiht der ganzen Konstruktion eine bessere Standhaftigkeit.

description.text:
This is a drop in replacement for the stock frame of a Gaui 330xs. The original frame was cheap and flimsy, and this has proven to be rock solid, better in a crash, and has better wire management. 
I've finished design on a few upgrades that make the frame much much tougher. A prop snapped today, and it fell a good ten feet and no breakage on the frame. This is a seriously high performance machine. 
Recent test went like this, take it up to ~30' turn on throttle hold, it hit the grass arm first with no damage!
Also, 3 kit versions are coming, along with some minor upgrades.

Print all parts at 40% infill
1 main section
4 arms
4 motor mounts Necessary parts:
8 m3x10 machine screws
4 m3x22 machine screws
Servo tape
Velcro tape
A gaui 330x kit, or equivalent. Instructions:
Print all the parts at 40% infill
Starting with one arm, place a motor in a motor mount, and bolt the combo to the arm, feeding the wires through the hole. Now place the speed controller in it's pocket, and attach the banana plugs. Repeat 3x
Now mount one arm into the main section by carefully running the wires into the main section, and through the holes in the top, then carefully run a m3x22 machine screw through the main section, GENTLY tighten. This is a tough material condition and is done so on purpose, so that it breaks in the event of a major crash because it is the quickest print.
Add velcro to the bottom, and mount all the electronics to the top with servo tape, and you're ready to fly, no soldering or modifying. Let me know how it treats you! This thing is in progress, and I will release a battery keeper.

description.text: I've been doing a lot of chemistry in my basement lately, but I have had a lot of trouble collecting gasses due to my lack of one of these.

NGSS CCSS

Gas Collection Every Chemistry class needs real, hands-on experiments to make learning fun. Some of the most fun I've had in chemistry class involves collecting hydrogen gas and sparking it to make the characteristic "bark", as well as the collection of oxygen gas to light a smoldering stick on fire.

To Collect and test Hydrogen Fill the bath about 2 cm deep with water. Submerge the test tube/graduated cylinder. Stand the test tube up so that it covers the hole in the bottom of the water bath. (Method 1) Add a known amount of 1M HCl to the "tank" through the hole in the top. Using stoichiometry, calculate the proper mass of zinc powder to add. The reaction that will occur is 2Zn+2HCl-->2ZnCl+H2. PLUG THE HOLE through which you added the zinc and acid.
(Method 2) Add a known amount of 1M NaOH to the "tank" through the hole in the top. Using stoichiometry, calculate the proper mass of aluminium (powdered or foil) to add. The reaction that will occur is 2Al + 2NaOH + 6H2O → 2NaAl(OH)4 + 3H2. PLUG THE HOLE through which you added the Aluminium and Base. Once bubbles start coming out the side of the tube, the tube is full. To test for hydrogen, take a match, light it, and hold it under the test tube. If the experiment was conducted correctly, there should be a loud "bark" or "oomph" sound. To collect and test Oxygen Fill the bath about 2 cm deep with water. Submerge the test tube/graduated cylinder. Stand the test tube up so that it covers the hole in the bottom of the water bath. Fill the "tank" with 3% H2O2, and add about a gram of zinc or other catalyst. PLUG THE HOLE through which you added the Zinc and Hydrogen Peroxide The zinc is a catalyst in the reaction, and thus the reaction is as follows: 2H202-->2H2O+O2. Once bubbles start coming out the side of the tube, the tube is full. To test for hydrogen, take a match, light it, and light a kebab skewer with the match. Blow the skewer out, and then, while the skewer is smoldering, place it in the oxygen-filled test tube. If the experiment was conducted correctly, the skewer should burst into flame.

Noticed that the original hypercube fan shroud only blew air on one side of my prints, so all my PLA prints had one side that would droop and look rough. This fan helps to accelerate the flow of air from the blower fan and directs it all around the part. So far with this fan I've had no problems with printing PLA and getting great overhangs/surface finish.

Took me about 10 design iterations to get this right and make it fit with the original induction probe that the Hypercube was designed for. Make sure to print it in a high temperature resistant material like PETG or ABS. I printed mine in PETG and it hasn't warped at all from heat coming from the hotend.

Finally the Stranger Things desk light is 99% done still waiting for a plasma ball but that's all for completion. Its a DIY project so with some building experience and a small amount of soldering skills you can make this as well.

1-Tips for building and covering the Case:
2-BOM:
3-Final Notes:

1-Tips
Glue the side plates that need the be together with CA place them on a flat surface then use activator for a fast bond of the CA glue.

To get a smooth looking surface on flat 3D printed parts like these use matt/flat picture paper (not glossy). Use Bizon Tix on the 3D part and paper to glue them in place it also helps a lot giving the case strength.

You can use basically all types of paint on the paper but make sure to give it at least 2 coats of primer or just normal paint because the paper will absorb a lot of paint in the beginning and looks funky

The red background behind the text is made from packaging material 'blister case' any type of transparent plastic will do you need to paint it red of course most common paints will do the trick. Red leds behind this background will light it up.

2-BOM Bill of Materials

6x 3mm red leds for the background (i used blue and red but only red is better)
Resistors for LED
2x USB Plasma Balls they are cheap to find on ebay around 6€ a piece
5v PSU (phone charger) 1A minimal
1x Power Jack 3 Pin Terminals 5.5 mm x 2.5mm DC Power
1x USB cable for power jack and PSU
5 meter (16 feet) of power cable must be enough connect it all i think
1x On-Off switch
8x Magnets to held the backdoor in place or use a other method because magnets are not so great for this...

Fiber Optic for the light i used 0.75mm you can find a roll on ebay or aliexpress or just buy a cheap fiber optic kids toy lamp and use that :)

RGB leds can be found on ebay make sure you choose the Slow blinking and Double legs. Those are ready to use and dont need any other then a resistor to do the job.

https://youtu.be/l-5ANK-_HGc

WARNING You need to disassemble the USB Plasma Balls in order to make it fit in the case. Plasma Balls use HIGH VOLTAGE it can kill you! So don't try this!
